snippet.title: What Happens If A Star Explodes Near The Earth?
snippet.description:
People have witnessed supernovae for millennia, but what threat do they pose to life on Earth? This video is sponsored by Brilliant. You can get started for free, or the first 200 people to sign up via https://brilliant.org/veritasium get 20% off a yearly subscription. 

‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ
A massive thanks to Prof. Hans-Thomas Janka for helping us with the physics of supernovae and GRBs. A massive thanks to Prof. Brian Thomas for all of his help with the terrestrial effects of supernovae and GRBs. This video would not have been possible without them. Also thanks to Dr. Luke Barnes for his initial help with the literature search.

Hydrogen bomb vs Supernova fact was taken from this great article by xkcd/Randall Munroe ‚Äì https://what-if.xkcd.com/73/ (based on the calculation by Andrew Karam, 2002)

Cosmic bubble footage from
https://www.cfa.harvard.edu/news/1000-light-year-wide-bubble-surrounding-earth-source-all-nearby-young-stars

Neutrino driven SN explosion simulations from https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/2041-8205/808/2/L42

‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ
References:

Melott, A. et al. (2019). Hypothesis: Muon radiation dose and marine megafaunal extinction at the End-Pliocene supernova. Astrobiology, 19(6), 825-830. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Melott1

Thomas, B. C. et al. (2016). Terrestrial effects of nearby supernovae in the early Pleistocene. The Astrophysical Journal Letters, 826(1), L3 ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Thomas1

Melott, A. L., & Thomas, B. C. (2019). From cosmic explosions to terrestrial fires?. The Journal of Geology, 127(4), 475-481. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Melott2

Fields, B. et al. (2019). Near-Earth supernova explosions: Evidence, implications, and opportunities. arXiv preprint arXiv:1903.04589. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Fields1

Thomas, B. C., Atri, D., & Melott, A. L. (2021). Gamma-ray bursts: not so much deadlier than we thought. Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society, 500(2), 1970-1973. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Thomas2

Melott, A. et al. (2004). Did a gamma-ray burst initiate the late Ordovician mass extinction?. International Journal of Astrobiology, 3(1), 55-61. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Melott3

Firestone, R. B. (2014). Observation of 23 supernovae that exploded less than 300 pc from Earth during the past 300 kyr. The Astrophysical Journal, 789(1), 29. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/firestone1

Janka, H. T. (2017). Neutrino emission from supernovae. arXiv preprint arXiv:1702.08713. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Janka1

Janka, H. T., & Hillebrandt, W. (1989). Neutrino emission from type II supernovae-an analysis of the spectra. Astronomy and astrophysics, 224, 49-56. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Janka2

Janka, H. T. (2017). Neutrino-driven explosions. arXiv preprint arXiv:1702.08825. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Janka3

Karam, P. A. (2002). Gamma and neutrino radiation dose from gamma ray bursts and nearby supernovae. Health physics, 82(4), 491-499. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Karam1

Melott, A. L., Thomas, et al.. (2017). A supernova at 50 pc: effects on the Earth's atmosphere and biota. The Astrophysical Journal, 840(2), 105. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Melott4

Ludwig, P., et al. (2016). Time-resolved 2-million-year-old supernova activity discovered in Earth‚Äôs microfossil record. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 113(33), 9232-9237. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Ludwig1

Gritschneder, et al. (2011). The supernova triggered formation and enrichment of our solar system. The Astrophysical Journal, 745(1), 22. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Gritschneder1

Motizuki, Y., Takahashi, et al. (2009). An Antarctic ice core recording both supernovae and solar cycles. arXiv preprint arXiv:0902.3446. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Motizuki

Zucker, C. et al. (2022). Star formation near the Sun is driven by expansion of the Local Bubble. Nature, 601(7893), 334-337. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Zucker1

Hirata, K. et al.(1987). Observation of a neutrino burst from the supernova SN1987A. Physical Review Letters, 58(14), 1490. ‚Äì https://ve42.co/Hirata1

snippet.title: Magic Mike‚Äôs Last Dance | Official Trailer
snippet.description:
Just in time for Valentine‚Äôs Day comes the third installment of the 
blockbuster ‚ÄúMagic Mike‚Äù film franchise, the musical comedy ‚ÄúMagic Mike‚Äôs Last 
Dance.‚Äù The creative team behind the first film, which garnered praise from critics 
and audiences alike, has reunited to create the magic again: Channing Tatum 
reprises his role as Mike Lane and Steven Soderbergh returns to the helm with a 
script from Reid Carolin, who also wrote the first two films. And starring alongside 
Tatum is Salma Hayek Pinault (‚ÄúHouse of Gucci,‚Äù ‚ÄúHitman‚Äôs Wife‚Äôs Bodyguard‚Äù).
‚ÄúMagic‚Äù Mike Lane (Tatum) takes to the stage again after a lengthy hiatus, 
following a business deal that went bust, leaving him broke and taking 
bartender gigs in Florida. For what he hopes will be one last hurrah, Mike heads 
to London with a wealthy socialite (Hayek Pinault) who lures him with an offer he 
can‚Äôt refuse‚Ä¶and an agenda all her own. With everything on the line, once Mike 
discovers what she truly has in mind, will he‚Äîand the roster of hot new dancers 
he‚Äôll have to whip into shape‚Äîbe able to pull it off?
The film‚Äôs producers are Nick Wechsler, Gregory Jacobs, Tatum, Carolin and 
Peter Kiernan. Julie M. Anderson serves as executive producer.
Also starring with Tatum and Hayek Pinault are Ayub Khan Din (‚ÄúAckley 
Bridge‚Äù), newcomer Jemelia George, Juliette Motamed (‚ÄúWe Are Lady Parts‚Äù) 
and Vicki Pepperdine (‚ÄúJohnny English Strikes Again‚Äù).
Soderbergh‚Äôs creative team behind the scenes includes production 
designer Pat Campbell (‚ÄúThe Bastard Son & The Devil Himself‚Äù), costume designer 
Christopher Peterson (‚ÄúThe Irishman‚Äù) and music supervisor Season Kent (‚ÄúKIMI,‚Äù 
‚ÄúLet Them All Talk‚Äù), with choreography by Alison Faulk and Luke Broadlick, both 
part of the ‚ÄúMagic Mike‚Äù franchise.
A Warner Bros. Pictures Presentation, ‚ÄúMagic Mike‚Äôs Last Dance‚Äù slides into 
theaters only in North America on February 10, 2023 and internationally beginning 
8 February 2023, and will be distributed worldwide by Warner Bros. Pictures
